            <pb n="2" facs="#f0001"/>
            <milestone unit="section" rendition="#hr"/>
            <lb break="yes"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#i">BARON DE HUMBOLDT.</hi>
                </head>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>
                    <hi rendition="#c">[FROM THE NATIONAL.]</hi>
                </p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>The death of M. William de Humboldt, formerly Prus-<lb break="no"/>sian Minister, has been announced in the journals. The<lb break="yes"/>public will, no doubt, be very glad to learn some details as<lb break="yes"/>to the last moments of this illustrious philologist. The<lb break="yes"/>following is an extract from a letter dated April 10, which<lb break="yes"/>M. Alexander Humboldt, the celebrated traveller, has<lb break="yes"/>written to M. Arago of the <hi rendition="#i">Institute:</hi> &#x2014;</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>&#x201C;I had the misfortune to lose my brother on the even-<lb break="no"/>ing before last. I am in the deepest affliction. In our<lb break="yes"/>greatest sorrows we think of those who are the most dear<lb break="yes"/>to us; I feel a little relieved in writing to you. ...<lb break="yes"/>We saw he was dying, for ten days. His weakness had<lb break="yes"/>cruelly increased for several weeks; a constant trembling<lb break="yes"/>took place in all his members, but his mind retained its<lb break="yes"/>full energy. He was always writing; he leaves two<lb break="yes"/>works nearly finished; one upon the languages of the In-<lb break="no"/>dian Archipelago, derived from the Sanscrit; the other<lb break="yes"/>upon the origin and the philosophy of languages in gene-<lb break="no"/>ral. These works will be published. My brother has left<lb break="yes"/>his manuscripts, some works he had begun, and his pre-<lb break="no"/>vious collection of books, to the public library. He died<lb break="yes"/>of an inflammation of the chest, and he watched the pro-<lb break="no"/>gress of the disease with an afflicting sagacity; he was en-<lb break="no"/>dowed with superior intelligence, and with a mind full of<lb break="yes"/>elevation and nobleness; I remain sadly isolated. I hope<lb break="yes"/>that I shall, at last, have the happiness of embracing you<lb break="yes"/>this year. ...</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>&#x201C;Tegel, near Berlin.&#x201D;</p>
            </div>
            <lb break="yes"/>
